{"add":{"doc":{"id":"bf9157505defb8909ea9ea9a28051fbb1ac64c61d65566299192221d192d123f","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/57/CorneliusVanderbiltStatue.JPG/230px-CorneliusVanderbiltStatue.JPG","previous":["The Vanderbilt Board of Trust in May 1962 voted to accept African Americans in all schools, and first undergraduates entered the school the fall of 1964.[19] The university drew national attention in 1966 when it recruited Perry Wallace, the first African-American athlete in the Southeastern Conference.[21] Wallace, from Nashville, played varsity basketball for Vanderbilt from 1967 to 1970, and faced considerable opposition from segregationists when playing at other Southeastern Conference venues.[22] In 2004, a student-led drive to retire Wallace's jersey finally succeeded.[22] Harold Stirling Vanderbilt was chairman of the Board of Trust between 1955 and 1968 when racial integration was a prominent topic at the school.[citation needed] Today, a statue of him in front of Buttrick Hall memorializes his efforts."],"after":["In 1966, the Oberlin Graduate School of Theology moved from Ohio to Nashville, and merged with the Vanderbilt Divinity School.[citation needed]"]}}}